'''Robert William Hay''' (1786–1861) was a British public official.

==Biography==

===Early life===
Robert William Hay was born in 1786 in [[Westminster]], [[London]], England.<ref name="anu">[http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/hay-robert-william-2171 Hay, Robert William (1786–1861)], ''[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]''</ref> His father was Reverend George William Auriol Hay-Drummond and his mother Elizabeth Margaret (Marshall) Hay-Drummond.<ref name="anu"/> His paternal grandfather was [[Robert Hay Drummond]] (1711–1776), who served as the [[Archbishop of York]] from 1761 to 1776.<ref name="anu"/>

He graduated from [[Christ Church, Oxford]], where he received a Bachelor of Arts degree in 1807 and a Master of Arts degree in 1809.<ref name="anu"/>

===Career===
From 1812 to 1824, he served as Private Secretary to [[Henry Dundas, 1st Viscount Melville]] (1742-1811), who was [[List of the First Lords of the Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]], and then served as [[Victualling Commissioners|Victualling Commissioner]] in the British [[Royal Navy]].<ref name="anu"/>

He served as the [[Under-Secretary of State for the Colonies|Permanent Under-Secretaries of State for the Colonies]] from 1825 to 1836.<ref name="anu"/><ref>Robert Charles Lee, ''The Canada Company and the Huron Tract, 1826-1853: Personalities, Profits and Politics'', Dundurn, 2004, p. 230 [https://books.google.com/books?id=BLsfrDfyH98C&pg=PA230&dq=%22Robert+William+Hay%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bc1dU5OHBsGIkQWhnIGwAg&ved=0CDEQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=%22Robert%20William%20Hay%22&f=false]</ref><ref>Kathleen Mary Butler, ''The Economics of Emancipation: Jamaica & Barbados, 1823-1843'', Chapel Hill, North Carolina: UNC Press Books, 1995, p. 26 [https://books.google.com/books?id=GRmjCYuLWD4C&pg=PA26&dq=%22Robert+William+Hay%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=hc5dU5WPDMGQkAXXvICgCw&ved=0CCwQ6AEwADgU#v=onepage&q=%22Robert%20William%20Hay%22&f=false]</ref> However, [[James Stephen (civil servant)|James Stephen]] (1789-1859) is credited with doing much of the work.<ref name="anu"/>

He was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in 1814.<ref> {{cite web|url=https://collections.royalsociety.org/DServe.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Persons&dsqPos=11&dsqSearch=%28%28text%29%3D%27hay%27%29|title= Fellows details|publisher= Royal Society|accessdate= 23 January 2017}} </ref>

===Death===
He died on May 9, 1861 in [[Malta]].<ref name="anu"/>

==Legacy==
*[[Hay Street, Perth|Hay Street]], a major road in the central business district of [[Perth]], Western Australia, is named in his honour.

